Project Overview

The telecom operator, Interconnect, has a goal to predict churn of their clients. The clients that plan to leave will be offered promotional codes and special plan options.

Goal: Categorize clients into two groups:

  • customers who will NOT churn
  • customers who WILL churn

Target: EndDate

  • A Date indicates the client has left
  • No indicates the client is active

  2. Incorrect Dtypes:
      

    • BeginDate: object --> datetime
        

      • contracts['BeginDate'] = pd.to_datetime(contracts['BeginDate'])
        • 

      

      • 

    • EndDate: object --> datetime
        

      • contracts['EndDate'] = pd.to_datetime(contracts['EndDate'])
        • 

      

      • 

    • TotalCharges: object --> float
        

      • contracts['TotalCharges'] = pd.to_numeric(contracts['TotalCharges'], errors='coerce')
        • 

      • errors='coerce' - turns problematic entries to NaN
        • 

      

      • 

    

    3. 

  3. Feature Engineer:
      

    • customerID: Leave as is
      • 

    • BeginDate: Extract month, year (not day: all days = 01)) for EDA
        

      • contracts['begin_year'] = contracts['begindate'].dt.year, contracts['begin_month'] = contracts['begindate'].dt.month
        • 

      • Once engineered get max and min month and year to get a general timeline of data collection
        • 

      • Drop for modeling after creating tenure_months
        • 

      

      • 

    • EndDate: No = 0 = Active; Date = 1 = NOT Active
        

      • 4 months make up ALL churned customers: 10/2019, 11/2019, 12/2019, 01/2020
        • 

      • drop for modeling - create churned instead
        • 

      

      • 

    • Create churned: Use EndDate to determine if the customer has churned or not
      • 

    • Create tenure_months for modeling (EndDate(no EndDate = February 2020) - BeginDate)
      • 

    • Type: Rows not necessary to standardize (Month-to-month, Two year, One year)
        

      • Consider OHE: pd.get_dummies(contracts, columns=['Type'], drop_first=True) Not Recommended for CatBoost
        • 

      

      • 

    • PaperlessBilling: Rows not necessary to standardize (Yes/No)
        

      • Consider Binary Encoding: contracts['PaperlessBilling'] = contracts['PaperlessBilling'].map({'Yes':1, 'No':0})
        • 

      

      • 

    • PaymentMethod: Rows not necessary to standardize (Bank transfer (automatic), Credit card (automatic), Electronic check, Mailed check)
        

      • Consider OHE: pd.get_dummies(contracts, columns=['PaymentMethod'], drop_first=True) Not Recommended for CatBoost
        • 

      

      • 

    • MonthlyCharges: Leave as is
      • 

    • TotalCharges: Leave as is (after changing to float dtype)
      •

                  'PaymentMethod': 'payment_method',

# Contracts Dataset

# Binary Encoding for 'paperless_billing', 
contracts['paperless_billing'] = contracts['paperless_billing'].map({'Yes':1, 'No': 0})

print("Contracts Dataset")
print("--------------------------------------------------")
display(contracts.info())
display(contracts.head())
print()


# Personal Dataset

# Binary Encoding for 'gender', 'partner', and 'dependents'
personal_col = ['partner', 'dependents']

for col in personal_col:
    personal[col] = personal[col].map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0})

personal['gender'] = personal['gender'].map({'Male': 1, 'Female': 0})

print("Personal Dataset")
print("--------------------------------------------------")
display(personal.info())
display(personal.head())
print()


# Internet

# Binary Encoding for 'internet_service', 'online_security', 'online_backup', 'device_protection', 'tech_support', 'streaming_tv', 'streaming_movies'
internet_col = ['online_security', 'online_backup', 'device_protection', 'tech_support', 'streaming_tv', 'streaming_movies']

for col in internet_col:
    internet[col] = internet[col].map({'Yes':1, 'No':0})

internet['internet_service'] = internet['internet_service'].map({'DSL': 1, 'Fiber optic': 0})

print("Internet Dataset")
print("--------------------------------------------------")
display(internet.info())
display(internet.head())
print()


# Phone

# Binary Encoding for 'multiple_lines'

In[16]:






# Create `tenure_months` - how many months a customer has been with the company
# No end_date = February, 2020

# Create temporary end_date
reference_date_active = pd.to_datetime('2020-02-01')
contracts['effective_end_date'] = contracts['end_date'].fillna(reference_date_active)
display(contracts.head())

# Get the length of time a customer has stayed in months - have to calculate using .dt.year and .dt.month separately
# Example: begin[2015-09] - end[2020-02] = 4 years and 5 months = 53 months
    # figure year: 2020 - 2015 = 5 years (convert to months by multiplying by 12) = 60 months
    # figure months: 02 months - 09 months = (-)7 months
    # Put it together: 2020 - 2015 = 5 years * 12 months = 60 months + (2 months - 9 months = (-)7 months) = 60 -7 = 53 months

contracts['tenure_months'] = ((contracts['effective_end_date'].dt.year - contracts['begin_date'].dt.year) * 12) + (contracts['effective_end_date'].dt.month - contracts['begin_date'].dt.month)

# Drop the temporary 'effective_end_date' column
contracts.drop(columns=('effective_end_date'), inplace = True)
display(contracts.head())

Reminder of joins:


    

  • inner: Keeps only customers present in all DataFrames
      

    • Not chosen: Not every customer has phone or internet services
      • 

    

    • 

  • left: Keeps all customers from the left DataFrame, adding data from the right
      

    • Chosen: The left dataframe will be contracts, which will add data from each dataframe (personal, internet, phone) using customer_id
      • 

    

    • 

  • outer: Keeps all customers from both
      

    • Not chosen: Would include customers outside the base contracts table, which is not wanted
      •

Key Insights:


1. Monthly charges and churn:


    

  • Churned customers consistently pay more than active customers.
    • 

  • Higher median and IQR values indicate that elevated charges are associated with increased churn risk across the population rather than being driven by outliers.
2. Tenure moderates churn risk:
    • 

  • The scatterplot shows that churn is highly concentrated in the first approximately 2530 months of tenure. The density of churned customers is much higher in this early period, particularly among those paying mid-to-high monthly charges (~60100+).
    • 

  • After approximately 30 months, churn becomes rare across all pricing tiers, suggesting that long-tenured customers develop stronger price tolerance and perceive higher value in the service.
3. Interaction between price and tenure:
    • 

  • Churn is not solely a function of price; it depends on the combination of tenure and monthly charges.
    • 

  • Early-tenure, higher-paying customers are the segment most at risk and therefore the most critical for retention efforts.
    • 



Conclusion


Churned customers tend to pay more than active customers, as reflected in higher medians and IQRs for monthly charges. The scatterplot clarifies that churn is primarily an early-tenure phenomenon, with most churn occurring within the first 2530 months. High monthly charges amplify churn risk in this early period, while tenure beyond this window strongly stabilizes retention. Retention strategies should therefore focus on early-stage, higher-value customers, as they are both the most price-sensitive and the most likely to churn.

    •

    • 

  • Categorical or binary features may not show strong linear correlation but can still be predictive when encoded (e.g., PaperlessBilling, ContractType, TechSupport).
    • 



Key Findings:


1. High-impact numeric features:


    

  • TenureMonths, BeginYear, MonthlyCharges, TotalCharges (careful with collinearity).
    • 



2. Categorical / binary features still important:


    

  • PaperlessBilling, ContractType, PaymentMethod, TechSupport, SeniorCitizen.
    • 

  • Correlation wont show much, but theyre clearly linked to churn shown by earlier EDA visualization.
    • 



3. Features with very low linear correlation (<0.1) are unlikely to help by themselves, but could still contribute in combination with others.






















EDA Conclusion
Exploratory data analysis reveals that customer churn affects roughly 26.5% of customers, with retention at 73.5%. Churn is predominantly an early-tenure phenomenon, heavily concentrated within the first ~2530 months. Customers who leave early often have higher monthly charges, shorter-term contracts, and specific behavioral patterns such as using Electronic Check payments or not subscribing to tech support.


Key patterns identified include:


1. Tenure:


    

  • Churned customers have a median tenure of 10 months (IQR 229), while active customers have a median of 38 months (IQR 1561).
    • 

  • Most churn occurs within the first 22.5 years, highlighting early-stage engagement as critical for retention.
    • 



2. Monthly Charges:


    

  • Churned customers pay more on average (median  80 USD) than active customers (median  64 USD).
    • 

  • Higher charges combined with short tenure represent the highest-risk segment.
    • 



3. Contract Type:


    

  • Month-to-month contracts have the highest churn rates (~4045%).
    • 

  • Longer contracts (one- or two-year) strongly reduce churn, with two-year contracts exhibiting churn as low as 15%.
    • 



4. Payment Method:


    

  • Customers using Electronic Check have the highest churn (~45%), largely due to concentration in month-to-month contracts and shorter tenure.
    • 

  • Automatic payments (Bank Transfer, Credit Card) are associated with higher retention (churn ~1517%).
    • 



5. Tech Support:


    

  • Customers with tech support churn at ~1217%, versus 3033% for those without.
    • 

  • Access to technical support is a strong retention factor.
    • 



6. Senior Citizens:


    

  • Seniors churn at nearly twice the rate of non-seniors (~4044% vs. 2125%).
    • 

  • Limited adoption of tech support among seniors likely contributes to higher churn.
    • 



Integrated insights:


    

  • High-risk segments are early-tenure, higher-paying customers, particularly those on month-to-month contracts using Electronic Check and without tech support.
    • 

  • Retention drivers include longer tenure, longer-term contracts, tech support access, and automatic payment methods.
    • 



These findings provide a clear foundation for predictive modeling, indicating that all available featuresnumeric, categorical, and binarymay contribute to identifying customers most likely to churn. Early intervention for high-risk segments, particularly new and higher-paying customers, is likely the most effective strategy for reducing churn.
